Overview

You walk in to your local department of motor registration office and see a long queue. It is the end of the month after all. You want to know the probability of spending less than 30 minutes because you have to go finish your school project. So you walk to the counter and ask one of the customers support reps how many customers an agent process per hour (rate). Once you learn the rate, you can derive the probability wait time using statistical model referred to as Exponential Distribution (ED).

Figure 1: A model graph of exponantial distribution overlayed on Normal distribution

When measuring the amount of time waiting in queue, weather it is at Starbucks or local super market or waiting support call phone queue, exponential distribution is used to quantify the probability wait time. For example using (ED), you can say “there is 45% probability that the wait is less than 15 minutes”, or more than “ 30 minutes”, or between “10 and 20 minutes” for a given queue.

Exponential Distribution is a probability distribution model that measures time between events that occur continuously and independently at a constant rate. In this paper we will demonstrate inferential data analysis for exponential distribution. The data for our analysis will be generated using a simulation code in R statistical programming. In this analysis, we will run 40 exponential distribution’s 10,000 times.

Inferential Analysis Objectives:

Once we have our data, we will focus on two areas of interest. First, we will examine the exponential distribution properties, mean and variability, from the simulated data and compare it against a theoretical properties of the distribution to see how far or close they are to each other. On the second part of the analysis, we will run the 40 exponential distribution 10, 100 times, again, this time with the average of the sample exponential distribution and check if the central limit theorem’s axiom that – regardless of the type of distribution the mean of sufficiently large random variable will approximate a normal distribution holds true. That is that will it resemble a bell curved normal distribution.

The probability density function (pdf) for exponantial distribution is:

\[f(x; \lambda ) = \begin{cases} \lambda e^{-\lambda x} & x\ge 0\\ 0 & x\le 0 \end{cases}\]

The total area under the exponential distribution, like normal distribution, is equal to 1. And here is mathematical derivation:

\[\int_{n=0}^{\infty} \lambda e^{-\lambda} = 1 \]

Examine the Properties (Q 1 & 2):

The rate for this excersise is given \[\lambda = 0.2\]

The mean (expected value) of the exponentially distributed random variable X with rate parameter lambda is given by: \[E[X] = 1 / \lambda - so we calculate the theoretical mean to be 1/0.2 = 5.\]

The variability for is: \[V[X] = 1/ \lambda ^2 - we calculate the theoretical variance 1/0.2 ^2 = 25\]

There fore Standard Deviation is \[SD[x] = \sqrt V[X] - we calculate the theoretical standard deviation \sqrt 25 = 5\]

Examine Eexponantial Distribution property for sampled & theoretical:

Here are the code chunks used to simulate exponantial distribution. The number of observation “n” is 40. The R function used to dervie the exponantial distribution is “rexp”. The code runs the “rexp”" function for 40 observation 1000 times.

x = NULL
#y = NULL
n <- 40 # number of observations
lambda <- .2 # rate \lambda

for (i in 1: 1000) x = c(x , rexp(n, lambda)) # 1000 simulation of ed

     hist(x, 
     xlim = c(min(x), max(x)),
     #ylim = c(0, .6),
     breaks = 30,
     probability = T, 
     col = "skyblue",
     main = "1000 Simulated Exponantial Distribution with labmbda = 0.2")

     lines(density(x), col='purple', lwd=3) #density map

rug(x)
abline(v = mean(x), col = "blue", lwd = 4)

legend(par('usr')[2], par('usr')[4], xjust=1,
       c('Mean', 'Density Overlay'),
       lwd=3,
       lty=1,
       col=c('blue', 'purple'))

Figure 2: A1 000 Simulated Exponantial Distributions with lambda 0.2 with density overlay

The Mean, variance and standard deviation for the exponantial distribution probablity are:

Exponential Distribution to Central Limit Theorem inference (Q 3)

Here we run the average of the 40 observed exponantial distribution a 1,000 times, and generate a histogram. As we can see it resembles a resembles a normal distribution bell curv. Confirming the Central Limit Theory that the mean of a large sample distributions, regardless of the type of distribution, will approximately resemble a normal distribution.

y = NULL
#y = NULL
n <- 40 # number of observations
lambda <- .2 # rate \lambda

for (i in 1: 1000) y = c(y , mean(rexp(n, lambda))) # mean of 40 exp at a rate of .2

hist(y, 
     xlim = c(min(y), max(y)),
     #ylim = c(0, .6),
     breaks = 30,
     probability = T, 
     col = "skyblue",
     main = "1000 Simulated Exponantial Distribution with labmbda = 0.2")

    lines(density(y), col='purple', lwd=3) #density map
rug(x)
## Warning in rug(x): some values will be clipped
abline(v = mean(y), col = "blue", lwd = 4)

legend(par('usr')[2], par('usr')[4], xjust=1,
       c('Mean', 'Density Overlay'),
       lwd=3,
       lty=1,
       col=c('blue', 'purple'))

Figure 3: A 1000 Simulated the averages of Exponantial Distributions with lambda 0.2 and density overlay

The following diagram shows a side by side view of the exponential distribution and the 40 averages of the exponential distribution. Here again we see that as large number of average distributions tend to approximate normal distribution. Normal distribution density curve overlay is added to show the how closely they resemble. On both cases, the mean is very close to 5, which is the theoretical mean value.

Figure 4: A 1000 Simulated the averages of Exponantial Distributions with lambda 0.2 and density overlay

Inferential observation:

The simulations and the analysis on this paper reveal that when sufficiently large, equally independent, sample random variables are fitted in an exponential distribution model, their properties, such as variability – mean – standard distribution, proves similar to the theoretical properties. And that, the arithmetic average of sufficiently large sampled exponential distribution show normal distribution tendency as postulated by the Central Limit Theorem.
